header.gameNote: SOUTHERN CONF TR AT CHARLESTON SC

article.headline: Appalachian St. 78, Western Carolina 59
article.story: NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- D.J. Thompson had 15 points, including four 3-pointers, to lead Appalachian State into the Southern Conference tournament semifinals for the third straight year with a 78-59 victory over Western Carolina on Thursday night. The No. 2 seed Mountaineers (25-6) have already set a school record for wins this season. They'll take on third-seeded College of Charleston on Friday night. Western Carolina (11-20) finished with 20 or more losses for the second time in three seasons. The Catamounts had already ended a losing streak in the tournament. Western Carolina's opening-round victory over Elon on Wednesday night was its first in the tournament since 2001. Early on, the Catamounts looked like they might keep the run going against Appalachian State, rushing out to a 16-12 lead. The Mountaineers soon recovered with a 19-7 run to gain a lead they would not give up. Ryann Abraham had six points and Demetrius Scott scored four points during the run, which put Appalachian State ahead 31-23. The Mountaineers built the margin to 19 after six straight points by Eduardo Bermudez made it 58-39 with 10:57 to go. Western Carolina closed to 59-48 on Antonio Russell's bucket about four minutes later. The Catamounts could not sustain the comeback. Freshman Nick Aldridge led Western Carolina with 24 points. Doug McLaughlin-Williams added 12 points for Appalachian State while Bermudez and Donte Minter finished with 11 each.
